@librasungirl I think the existing code already does what you are proposing (i.e. it accepts `service data len >= size=2`) and should work fine if additional fields are added in future to service data (i.e., device running the current code would accept them as valid and ignore the additional data). 

Maybe I am missing something here. Let me describe the code:

```c++
    uint8_t           serviceData = DnsSrpAnycast::kServiceNumber;
    const ServiceTlv *tlv         = aIterator.mServiceTlv;

    do
    {
        tlv = Get<Leader>().FindNextMatchingService(tlv, kThreadEnterpriseNumber, &serviceData, sizeof(serviceData));
        VerifyOrExit(tlv != nullptr, error = kErrorNotFound);

    } while (tlv->GetServiceDataLength() < sizeof(DnsSrpAnycast::ServiceData));
```

- The `serviceData` we are using in `FindNextMatchingService()` is just a single byte, so `sizeof(serviceData)` is 1.
  - In the call to `FindNextMatchingService()` we are basically accepting any service where the first byte matches the `DnsSrpAnycast::kServiceNumber (0x5c)`.
  - We then later check if there are any other fields after the service number.
- The check in `while()` loop `tlv->GetServiceDataLength() < sizeof(DnsSrpAnycast::ServiceData)` ensures that the service data is at least the minimum length we expect (or `2`) - we skip over any matching service that does not have the minimum expected length (we currently know)
   - Of course, if in future we add more fields to service data,  the code needs to change to handle the new fields and handle the backward compatibility, e.g., future/new code adding one more byte to service data may accept both size 2 or 3 or more and in case of an entry we size of 2 we need to define how to set the missing info (init with some default value, etc,). This is up to new code/spec (when/if there is a change to service data format). 
   - But any device running the current code (i.e., old code) would continue to work correctly.
- I think we even cover the extra bytes in service data in the unit test `TestNetworkDataDsnSrpServices()` (i.e. we have an entry in Network Data example in this test with some additional bytes in service data after the 2 and we ensure that it is accepted and parsed correctly).
- Do you see any concern with this? Thanks.

