The 4th parameter of `toOutputWithContext` is `forceSecretVal *bool`, and it forces the value to be a secret on resolution:

https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi/blob/0b13e67b0a89f3ee03ca3e243e70a93386653a8e/sdk/go/pulumi/types.go#L895-L914

However, if this feels race-y still, line 905-907 could be moved above the `go func()` here and directly set output.getState().secret. 

That said, I think `secret`, `known`, and `deps` should all be considered illegal to read from until awaited. Any code that reads those fields before the await will have incomplete information in the case of nested outputs:

```go
// unwrap an Output[Output[T]]
someOutput.ApplyT(func (x AnyOutput) {
  return x
})
```

Or a concrete example, summing two int outputs without using .All():

```go
xOutput.ApplyT(func (x int) IntOutput {
  return yOutput.ApplyT(func (y int) IntOutput {
    return x + y
  }).(IntOutput)
}).(IntOutput)
```

This latter output has the combined known-ness, secret-ness, and dependencies of both xOutput and yOutput, but that can't be known until the outer output is awaited (which will await the inner and accumulate.)

